WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.280
Hi everybody. Thank you. My name is Tyler Morgan-Wall and today I'm going to be talking

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:18.840
to you about 3D mapping, plotting, and printing with rayshader.

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:23.180
So a little about myself. I have a PhD in physics from Johns Hopkins University and

00:00:23.180 --> 00:00:28.639
I work at the Institute for Defense Analyses in Alexandria, Virginia. I'm the developer

00:00:28.639 --> 00:00:35.099
of four packages, rayshader, skipper, rayfocus, and adjusted cranlogs, but this slide mostly

00:00:35.099 --> 00:00:41.279
exists in case you don't recognize me from my very outdated Twitter profile picture because

00:00:41.279 --> 00:00:47.480
we all look a little different on the internet. I'm going to answer a few questions in this

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:52.400
talk. First and foremost, what is rayshader, why did I develop it, and how can you use

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:58.060
it to make beautiful maps and visualizations? Second, I'm going to spend a few minutes trying

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:02.680
to convince you that 3D plots aren't as bad as some people make them out to be and can

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:07.599
be an effective tool in your visualization arsenal. And finally, I'm going to talk a

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:12.919
bit about some of the non-coding activities that you can do to develop your projects and

00:01:12.919 --> 00:01:18.080
how you can take advantage of the great R community.

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:24.519
Rayshader is a package designed to create maps in R. And by create maps, I mean generating

00:01:24.519 --> 00:01:31.279
maps directly from elevation data. This is in contrast to building maps off of preexisting

00:01:31.279 --> 00:01:37.360
tiles. There's nothing wrong with using tiles to build your map, but it does limit your

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:43.239
aesthetic options to whatever the creator of those tiles decided on. By generating our

00:01:43.239 --> 00:01:50.620
maps directly from the source elevation data, we can have full control over their appearance.

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:57.260
So this is what happens when you plot elevation data with base R using the image function.

00:01:57.260 --> 00:02:02.000
The code is on the left and the output is on the right. This is Hobart, Tasmania, but

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.779
looks more like two amoebas dueling it out in pond scum, or as base R calls it, terrain

00:02:08.779 --> 00:02:19.779
colors. Here, the Hobart object is nothing more than a base R matrix. Here is the rayshader

00:02:20.059 --> 00:02:25.220
version of that plot using spherical shading. It's a much more naturalistic view of the

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:31.100
data. While you lose the direct mapping of color to elevation, you gain a much more human

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:36.460
understanding of the landscape's contours. Note how details appeared that weren't apparent

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:43.460
in the base R plot, namely the fact that there is a river between these two mountains.

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:48.300
Rayshader is built around elevation data, and building a plot works similarly to how

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:55.300
you build a plot in ggplot with layers. Here, I've added a water layer simply by calling

00:02:55.580 --> 00:03:01.500
the detect water and add water functions in rayshader with the elevation matrix. This

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:07.179
overlays a water layer on top of the sphere shade layer. Now, rayshader's name comes from

00:03:07.179 --> 00:03:13.179
the fact that it uses ray tracing to shade topographic maps, so much like we added our

00:03:13.259 --> 00:03:19.380
water layer here. We can add a shadow layer simply by calling the add shadow function

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:25.259
with the rayshade function. This traces rays from each point on the elevation matrix, determines

00:03:25.259 --> 00:03:31.179
if that point is in shadow or light, and shades it appropriately. The add shadow function layers

00:03:31.179 --> 00:03:37.899
it onto the existing plot, passed in using the pipe operator. We can continue stacking

00:03:37.899 --> 00:03:42.580
different types of shadows with additional calls to add shadow. Here, we add an ambient

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:48.419
occlusion layer, which models atmospheric scattering and makes valleys darker than ridges.

00:03:48.419 --> 00:03:54.740
We now have, in my opinion, a beautiful 2D topographic map, but if you think about it,

00:03:54.740 --> 00:04:01.740
our data is already inherently 3D, X, Y, and Z elevation. So, in rayshader, transitioning

00:04:03.179 --> 00:04:10.179
from 2D to 3D is as simple as swapping out the plot map function with the plot 3D function.

00:04:11.179 --> 00:04:18.179
Note how the only data used to generate all of this is the base R matrix, no special data

00:04:18.299 --> 00:04:23.420
structures. Once you're able to get your data into that form, you can focus solely on perfecting

00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:30.420
the aesthetics of your map. Speaking of aesthetics, changing them in rayshader is incredibly simple.

00:04:32.019 --> 00:04:37.220
There are seven built-in palettes, and you can create your own using the create texture

00:04:37.260 --> 00:04:44.260
function. The last one is the unicorn palette. However, one thing that bothered me when I

00:04:46.179 --> 00:04:51.820
first made that plot was, although it is very cool, as a 3D surface, it was representing

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:57.619
solid earth, but the plot itself looked flimsy and infinitesimally thin, like you could just

00:04:57.619 --> 00:05:04.320
blow it away if you breathed too hard. So, I made it so you could set solid equals true

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:10.000
in the plot 3D function, and rayshader would automatically render a solid 3D object. This

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.519
changes the aesthetic from pseudo-3D surface to actual 3D model, something you could imagine

00:05:16.519 --> 00:05:22.140
holding in your hand, putting at your desk, and fidgeting around with. You don't have

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:29.140
to imagine, though, because I built into rayshader the ability to export your maps to a 3D printable

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:35.140
format with no external software required.

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:42.140
So, this is Hobart, Tasmania, the same place. Note that the top figure is rendered in rayshader,

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:52.140
and the bottom figure is rendered in real life. Note how closely the two matches as

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:57.140
it rotates, and compare the similarity to the shadows on the surface of the 3D model.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:04.140
I have the model right here with me if you want to see me afterwards and check it out.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:11.140
Most importantly, adding this feature led me to the moment I knew I had made it as an R programmer.

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:18.140
Because my cat finally showed an interest in what I was doing.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:26.140
So, none of the built-in datasets in R really showcased all these features, so I included

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:33.739
a new dataset with rayshader of Monterey Canyon in Monterey Bay, California. Here, you can

00:06:33.739 --> 00:06:39.980
see where rayshader really starts to shine. Combined representations of 3D representations

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:43.140
of topographic and bathymetric data.

00:06:43.140 --> 00:06:48.140
So, our planet is going through an immense period of change, and much of that change

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:53.140
is focused around our coasts. One of the main goals I had with rayshader was to make it

00:06:53.140 --> 00:07:00.140
dead simple to make beautiful, engaging visualizations combining land and water. Here, all the user

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:05.140
has to do to model a changing coastline is to set the depth of the water in either plot

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:12.140
3D or the render water function. Rayshader handles all of the rendering and slicing.

00:07:14.140 --> 00:07:19.459
A good visualization needs context, and the render label function allows you to drop labels

00:07:19.459 --> 00:07:25.540
seamlessly into your maps, just with the row and column index in your matrix. The render

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:32.299
label you can easily customize with your line shape, font width, height, color, anything.

00:07:32.299 --> 00:07:39.299
You can do an RGL. So, annotating your maps is a very serious use of rayshader. This is

00:07:40.299 --> 00:07:47.299
not. But, in addition to adding shadow and water layers, you can also overlay arbitrary

00:07:50.299 --> 00:07:55.299
images and data on your maps. Normally, you could imagine this being used for something

00:07:55.299 --> 00:08:01.299
serious like, you know, public health data or pollution statistics, but so far I've mostly

00:08:01.299 --> 00:08:08.299
used it to throw animated GIFs on my maps. Your visualization is your choice.

00:08:08.299 --> 00:08:15.299
One issue, though, I had with the raw 3D visualizations is how CG they looked. I wanted

00:08:15.299 --> 00:08:20.299
rayshader's output to look like a real model. So, one way to do that was to make it look

00:08:20.299 --> 00:08:30.299
like it was being imaged by a real camera. So, this is the render depth function, where

00:08:30.299 --> 00:08:37.299
I built a virtual camera into rayshader that simulates a depth of field effect. The interface

00:08:38.299 --> 00:08:44.299
to do this is dead simple. You just pass in a focal point and focal lens or f-stop, and

00:08:44.299 --> 00:08:49.299
you just call the render depth function, and then rayshader renders this beautiful post-processing

00:08:49.299 --> 00:08:58.299
bokeh effect. Finally, you're not limited to square maps with rayshader anymore. Simply

00:08:58.299 --> 00:09:04.299
by setting the points you want to remove to NA, R's missing value, you can shape your

00:09:04.299 --> 00:09:10.299
map into anything you want. Rayshader intelligently slices and renders the resulting map, and

00:09:10.299 --> 00:09:18.299
you can 3D print it. So, it's an easy gift for all of your geographically inclined friends.

00:09:18.299 --> 00:09:22.299
So, all of that covers the current state of rayshader, but there's a lot of cool features

00:09:22.299 --> 00:09:26.299
coming soon, several of which I'm excited to announce for the first time here at our

00:09:26.299 --> 00:09:33.299
studio conference. So, soon you're going to be able to explore your rayshader visualizations

00:09:33.299 --> 00:09:40.299
in virtual reality, augmented reality, as compact HTML-embeddable 3D assets, and in

00:09:40.299 --> 00:09:47.299
external 3D software such as Blender. And this is possible because I added to rayshader

00:09:47.299 --> 00:09:56.299
the ability to export to GLTF 2.0, which is the next-gen 3D asset file transmission format.

00:09:56.299 --> 00:10:00.299
So, this means your data visualizations are no longer stuck in R. You can include them

00:10:00.299 --> 00:10:06.299
in your, you can make them, put them in the web and include them in standard 3D graphics

00:10:06.299 --> 00:10:14.299
workflows. So, that sums up the current and future state of rayshader, but I think I know

00:10:14.299 --> 00:10:27.299
what many people came here to see. 3D GG plots, which are coming next. That will be in the

00:10:27.299 --> 00:10:34.299
next release of rayshader. But before I release this to the public, I do need to address the

00:10:34.299 --> 00:10:38.299
small contingency of people who would say that I shouldn't even release this feature

00:10:38.299 --> 00:10:44.299
because 3D plots only exist to impede interpretation and are an affront to good visualization

00:10:44.299 --> 00:10:55.299
practices. So, are 3D plots always bad? No. The idea of 3D plots being bad stems from

00:10:55.299 --> 00:11:01.299
the fact that 3D has often been used gratuitously, where the data itself is inherently 2D or

00:11:01.299 --> 00:11:08.299
1D and 3D is just added for visual fluff. When a data has legitimate 3D mapping, creating

00:11:08.299 --> 00:11:14.299
a 3D plot is perfectly fine. There's also the idea that since the display medium is 2D,

00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:20.299
3D plots are not appropriate. So, here's two examples from the source of all things

00:11:20.299 --> 00:11:26.299
cartographic in the USGS. The Atlas of Oblique Maps, published in 1988, contains beautiful

00:11:26.299 --> 00:11:33.299
3D representations of topographic and bathymetric data. Unlike a 2D contour or color map, you

00:11:33.299 --> 00:11:37.299
don't need to have a degree in cartography or to read a color bar to know what's going

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:44.299
on. The 3D structure of the landscape is immediately apparent. Some might say, well, that's just

00:11:44.299 --> 00:11:50.299
illustration. That's not data viz. But that's not the case. The cartographers of the USGS

00:11:50.299 --> 00:11:55.299
actually created these maps by using what's called an isometrograph, which maps contours

00:11:55.299 --> 00:12:04.299
to their 3D projection. These maps were based off of actual data visualized in 3D. And even

00:12:04.299 --> 00:12:09.299
in 1988, cartographers understood something very important about these types of visualizations.

00:12:10.299 --> 00:12:16.299
They are incredibly engaging and easy to understand. And this type of engaging tool is important

00:12:16.299 --> 00:12:22.299
when trying to communicate complex ideas and analyses about our changing planet.

00:12:22.299 --> 00:12:27.299
Each visualization is part of a story, and sometimes the idea that the visualization

00:12:27.299 --> 00:12:31.299
needs to be so precisely constructed that the reader could take a ruler to the plot

00:12:31.299 --> 00:12:35.299
and reconstruct the data set manually needs to take a backseat to the story you're trying

00:12:35.299 --> 00:12:41.299
to tell. This visualization was not made with RayShader, but I thought it was a great

00:12:41.299 --> 00:12:46.299
example of a 3D map that tells a story on its own. The change in groundwater in Southern

00:12:46.299 --> 00:12:51.299
California over time shows how the water table is breathing. Would this visualization be

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:57.299
as effective or engaging without the 3D? I don't think so. The 3D brings the data to

00:12:57.299 --> 00:13:03.299
life in a way a color map or a use of small multiples wouldn't. This animation is likely

00:13:03.299 --> 00:13:10.299
what caused this article to go viral and be exposed to thousands of people. And science

00:13:10.299 --> 00:13:15.299
that is communicated to the general public and stokes their interest is infinitely more

00:13:15.299 --> 00:13:21.299
valuable than science that just stokes the interest of those in academia. And 3D visualizations

00:13:21.299 --> 00:13:27.299
are a great way to do just that. So finally, I'm going to talk a bit about

00:13:27.299 --> 00:13:32.299
how non-coding activities can propel your projects forward. As I found out with RayShader

